Apple was hit by a huge outage this afternoon as thousands complained they were unable to access various products. The App store, iCloud and Apple Maps are said to have been impacted by the problem, but by Monday evening, the company said all of its services had been restored. According to Downdetector, which monitors real-time problems and outages, popular Apple services including Find My Phone, iTunes, Apple Music and iMessage have been also affected. Many Apple users expressed their frustration on Twitter after noticing their favourite apps stopped working from around 4.30pm UK time, with nearly a dozen services impacted. Apple’s system status page had showed 11 outages including podcasts, music and arcade. It said the company was investigating the issue, which impacted customers both here and across the Atlantic. It also left employees unable to working from home and has prevented retail staff from doing their job, Bloomberg reports. Lack of access to Maps has prompted Twitter users to joke about their reliance on the app. Product repairs, swaps and item pick-ups have also had to be temporarily halted. Apple’s system status page showed 11 ongoing outages including podcasts, music and arcade. It said the company was investigating the issue and warned services may be slow or unavailable. The company is responding to individual users via its Apple Support Twitter account – mainly sending a generic message saying: ‘Thanks for reaching out. Our team will review your message as soon as possible.’ Metro.co.uk has contacted the company for comment. Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. For more stories like this, check our news page. MORE : Apple HQ partially evacuated after envelope with white powder substance was discovered